    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Glutathione Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is glutathione and why is it called the master antioxidant?</summary>
      <p>Glutathione is a tripeptide composed of glutamine, cysteine, and glycine — produced by every cell in the body. It earns the "master antioxidant" title because it neutralizes free radicals, regenerates other antioxidants like vitamins C and E, and serves as the liver's primary detoxification molecule. Unlike other antioxidants, glutathione can be recycled back to its active form by glutathione reductase, making it uniquely sustainable in protecting cells from oxidative damage.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do glutathione gummies actually brighten skin?</summary>
      <p>Yes. A 2017 randomized controlled trial in <em>Clinical, Cosmetic and Investigational Dermatology</em> found that 250mg oral glutathione daily for 12 weeks significantly reduced melanin index and improved skin brightness. The mechanism involves inhibiting tyrosinase enzyme activity and shifting melanin synthesis from dark eumelanin to lighter pheomelanin. Results typically become visible after 8 to 12 weeks of consistent daily use.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between reduced glutathione and liposomal glutathione?</summary>
      <p>Reduced glutathione (GSH) is the active electron-donating form. Standard oral reduced glutathione faces partial digestive degradation before absorption. Liposomal glutathione encapsulates GSH within phospholipid bilayers that protect it through digestion and enhance absorption. A 2015 European Journal of Nutrition study found liposomal glutathione raised blood GSH levels 40% more than standard glutathione at the same dose.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much glutathione should I take daily?</summary>
      <p>Clinical studies use 250mg to 1,000mg daily. For skin brightening, 250 to 500mg daily is effective based on controlled trials over 8 to 12 weeks. For general antioxidant support, 500mg is the most commonly recommended dose. Liposomal forms may achieve comparable effects at lower doses due to enhanced bioavailability. Start at the lower end and increase if needed.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take glutathione with vitamin C?</summary>
      <p>Yes — this combination is both safe and synergistic. Vitamin C helps recycle oxidized glutathione (GSSG) back to active reduced form (GSH), extending glutathione's antioxidant lifespan. Research shows vitamin C supplementation alone increased intracellular glutathione by 18%. Taking both together enhances skin brightening through two independent melanin-reducing pathways.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How long does it take for glutathione gummies to work?</summary>
      <p>Antioxidant effects begin immediately at the cellular level. Subjective improvements in energy and wellbeing are typically noticed within 2 to 4 weeks. Skin brightening requires 8 to 12 weeks of consistent daily supplementation at 250mg or more. A 2017 clinical trial showed significant melanin index reduction at the 12-week mark. Detoxification support may produce effects within 2 to 6 weeks.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are glutathione gummies safe for daily use?</summary>
      <p>Oral glutathione has demonstrated excellent safety in clinical studies lasting up to 6 months at 250 to 1,000mg daily. A safety review in <em>Toxicology Letters</em> found no significant adverse effects. Mild GI symptoms may occur at higher doses. Consult your healthcare provider if pregnant, breastfeeding, taking immunosuppressants, or undergoing chemotherapy.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What depletes glutathione levels in the body?</summary>
      <p>Major depleting factors include aging (10% decline per decade after 20), chronic stress, poor sleep, excessive alcohol, environmental toxins, acetaminophen use, intense exercise, processed food diets, chronic infections, and UV exposure. Supporting natural production through NAC, sulfur-rich foods like cruciferous vegetables, and adequate protein also helps maintain levels alongside supplementation.</p>
    </details>

